=begin pod

=head1 05. Iteration

Building a reliable DSL pipeline is rarely one-shot. The typical workflow is a
short loop: run → observe → tighten → repeat.

=head2 The iteration loop

=begin code
1. Write grammar + prompt
2. Run against a sample input
3. Inspect the canonical DSL the LLM produced
4. If the grammar rejects it — tighten the prompt or relax the token
5. If the grammar accepts it but the data is wrong — tighten the token
6. Repeat until the full sample set passes
=end code

=head2 Logging the canonical DSL

Always log the intermediate DSL string so you can see exactly what the LLM
produced before the grammar runs:

=begin code :lang<raku>
sub parse-booking(Str $text --> Str) is export {
    my $canonical = normalize-text($text);
    note "canonical: $canonical";          # ← add during development
    my $match = Slangify::Tutorial::Grammar.parse(
        $canonical,
        :actions(Slangify::Tutorial::Actions.new)
    );
    die "Parse failed on: $canonical" unless $match;
    $match.made.raku
}
=end code

The C<note> line writes to C<STDERR> so it doesn't pollute the JSON output.
Remove it once the grammar is stable.

=head2 Common iteration scenarios

=head4 LLM uses the wrong field name

The LLM outputs C<guests 4> instead of C<party 4>. Fix: add an alias example
to the prompt, or rename the token to match natural LLM output.

=head4 LLM adds extra fields

The LLM outputs C<name "Jane" party 4 time 19:30 restaurant "Bistro Verde" date tomorrow notes "window seat">.
The grammar rejects it because C<notes> is unknown. Fix: either add a C<notes>
token to the grammar, or add a rule to the prompt: C<Output ONLY the five
specified fields>.

=head4 LLM drops optional fields

The LLM omits C<date> when it is not mentioned. Fix: make the token optional
in C<TOP> with C<?>  and handle the missing case in C<Booking>.

=head4 Token too strict

Your C<token time { <[0..2]>\d ':' <[0..5]>\d }> rejects C<9:00> (single
digit hour). Fix: C<token time { \d\d? ':' <[0..5]>\d }>.

=head2 Using the Slangify Playground for iteration

Paste your grammar into L<https://slangify.org> and type DSL lines directly
to test token rules without any LLM round-trip. Fast feedback for grammar
iteration.

=end pod
